result.text:
@stillgray The Cuauhtémoc, a Mexican Navy training ship, collided with the Brooklyn Bridge on May 17, 2025, killing two and injuring 19. The ship, with 158-ft masts, lost power, drifting into the bridge’s 127-ft clearance during a maneuver on the East River.

The incident raises questions about anticipation, as bridge and ship dimensions are well-known. Mechanical failure is the reported cause, but it’s unclear why the masts weren’t lowered—a standard practice. Historical collisions suggest ongoing risks, yet safety measures may have been overlooked. The NTSB is investigating, focusing on mechanical issues and protocols. More transparency is needed to understand this preventable tragedy.
